Visual Novels in the West, and what Makes them Sell

by Isaac Minn

Introduction: What are Visual Novels?

Visual Novels are a form of visual media that can be seen as a combination of a novel and a computer game. They're games with a text-based storyline and (usually) little interaction from the player, with the main appeal being the actual story being told. They originated in and are still prevalent in Japan, with western releases becoming more popular only within the last decade. Some western releases are localizations of originally Japanese games, with many of the older releases being fan-translations, and more recently, official localizations done by dedicated localization companies. Other western releases include games that are not of Japanese origin, but many of these games still take elements and inspiration from the classic Japanese visual novel.

In this tutorial, we'll be focusing on visual novels that originate in Japan, and what features about them make their localized releases sell (or not sell) in the west.

Data Collection

This is where we cover the first stage of the Data Science life cycle: the Data Collection stage. As this tutorial plans to analyze some of the common features among well-received visual novels in the west, we need an appropriate data source with relevant information. We will be using the Visual Novel Database, aka VNDB as our primary data source, as it provides not only information on individual visual novels in the form of tags (think genres or primary elements of a story), but also a general measure of public reception of players in the form of user votes on a 1-10 scale.

One nice thing about working with VNDB is that it offers dump files of the entire database updated daily, here. We will be using the Near-complete database from this page, as it contains all the information we need in a single PostgreSQL database.

Setting Up PostgreSQL on Your Machine

After downloading the database dump from VDNB, we can host the PSQL database on our local machine to access it If you're running Debian,

tar -I zstd -xvf vndb-db-latest.tar.zst

sudo apt update
sudo apt install postgresql postgresql-contrib
sudo service postgresql start

sudo -u postgres createuser --superuser <user_name>
psql -h localhost -U <user_name>

Now, once you're in SQL

CREATE DATABASE vndb
\i /path/to/database.sql

In our case, the database.sql file should be named import.sql

To check whether you've set it up correctly, in bash do psql -U <user_name> -d my_database

And then in SQL, \dt to list all tables. Our tables should be there.

We filter by olang = 'ja' for now, as the majority of visual novels originate from Japan, and we are interested in the inherent qualities of foreign visual novels whose localizations do well in the West.

Now that we know our database is working, let's modify our query a bit so we can find the information we want.

In[]:
query_releases = """
WITH rels AS (
    SELECT
        releases_vn.vid AS id,
        releases.id AS release_id,
        releases.olang AS release_lang,
        releases.released
    FROM releases_vn
    LEFT JOIN releases 
    ON releases.id = releases_vn.id
    ORDER BY id
),
jpvns AS (
    SELECT
        vn.id,
        vn_titles.title,
        vn.c_votecount,
        vn.c_rating,
        vn.c_average,
        vn.length,
        vn_titles.lang
    FROM vn 
    LEFT JOIN vn_titles
    ON vn.id = vn_titles.id
    WHERE olang = 'ja'
), 
r0 AS (
    SELECT
        rels.id,
        rels.release_lang,
        rels.release_id,
        rels.released AS release_date,
        jpvns.title,
        jpvns.c_votecount,
        jpvns.c_rating,
        jpvns.c_average,
        jpvns.length,
        jpvns.lang AS title_lang
    FROM rels
    LEFT JOIN jpvns
    ON rels.id = jpvns.id
    WHERE lang = 'ja'
    AND c_votecount > 50
    AND length != 0
)
SELECT *
FROM r0
"""

query = """SELECT *
FROM releases
"""
#teste = pd.read_sql(query, engine)

#access db and read query results
vns = pd.read_sql(query_releases, engine)

def get_earliest_lang_release(df, lang):
    df_filtered = df[df['release_lang'] == lang]
    df_filtered = df_filtered.sort_values(by='release_id')
    df_filtered = df_filtered.drop_duplicates(subset=['id'])
    
    return df_filtered

#make sure we are using the earliest release (the original japanese release) so we can compare popularity and score vs release date later
vns_temp = vns
vns_temp['release_id'] = pd.to_numeric(vns_temp['release_id'].apply(lambda x: x[1:]))
vns_unique_ja = get_earliest_lang_release(vns_temp, 'ja')
vns_unique_ja = vns_unique_ja.sort_values(by='c_average', ascending=False)
vns_unique_en = get_earliest_lang_release(vns_temp, 'en')
vns_unique_en = vns_unique_en.sort_values(by='c_average', ascending=False)
format_str = '%Y%m%d'
vns_unique_ja['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(vns_unique_ja['release_date'], format=format_str, errors='coerce')
vns_unique_en['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(vns_unique_en['release_date'], format=format_str, errors='coerce')
display(vns_unique_ja)
display(vns_unique_en)

With our new query, we're able to find a list of all visual novels that were developed and published in Japan. We also sort by average user vote and exclude visual novels that have less than 50 votes, and create two separate pandas dataframes - one for the first Japanese release of a game, and one for the first english release of a game.

Let's see what insights we can gather from this data.

In[]:
#Let's try mapping game length vs average score, to see if there's much correlation
#VNDB categorizes length into 6 categories
# 1 = Very Short (< 2h)
# 2 = Short (2h - 10h)
# 3 = Medium (10h - 30h)
# 4 = Long (30h - 50h)
# 5 = Very Long (50h+)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2)

ax[0, 0].scatter(list(vns_unique_ja['length']), list(vns_unique_ja['c_average']), marker='x', alpha=.2, color='blue')
ax[0, 0].set_title('Game length vs Avg Score JA')
ax[0, 0].set_xlabel('Length')
ax[0, 0].set_ylabel('Average Score')

slope, intercept = np.polyfit(list(vns_unique_ja['length']), list(vns_unique_ja['c_average']), 1)
x_fit = np.linspace(min(list(vns_unique_ja['length'])), max(list(vns_unique_ja['length'])), 100)
y_fit = slope * x_fit + intercept
ax[0, 0].plot(x_fit, y_fit, color='black', label='Regression Line')
ax[0, 0].legend()
ax[0, 0].xaxis.set_ticks(np.arange(1,6,1))

#Now let's map game length vs vote count
ax[1, 0].scatter(list(vns_unique_ja['length']), list(vns_unique_ja['c_votecount']), marker='x', alpha=.2, color='blue')
ax[1, 0].set_title('Game length vs Popularity (Votecount) JA')
ax[1, 0].set_xlabel('Length')
ax[1, 0].set_ylabel('Popularity')

slope, intercept = np.polyfit(list(vns_unique_ja['length']), list(vns_unique_ja['c_votecount']), 1)
x_fit = np.linspace(min(list(vns_unique_ja['length'])), max(list(vns_unique_ja['length'])), 100)

ax[1, 0].plot(x_fit, y_fit, color='black', label='Regression Line')

As our linear regression models show, there seems to be a generally positive correlation between a visual novel's length and its average score for both Japanese and English releases. This makes sense: users are not as likely to finish a very long game they don't enjoy compared to a shorter game. On the contrary, our regression model for game length vs popularity does not say much, but it's important to note that longer games generally seem to have more "popular" entries that many users have played than shorter games do.

While the data spread for release date vs average score for Japanese releases doesn't reveal much correlation, other than the fact that there are a lot more visual novels with 50+ votes that came out after the year 2004 than before, the English side is a different story. It is clear that there is a high concentration of visual novels that has an english release after 2022 with more than 50 votes, suggesting that either visual novels have increased in popularity since 2022, or that the community is paying more attention to newer releases than older ones, or both. It is important not to misunderstand the data here, however. The release date in the english plots represents its english release, not the original release date.

Let's merge the two dataframes so we get a single dataframe with only visual novels that have English releases, but keeping the original Japanese release date.

In[]:
merged_vns = vns_unique_ja.merge(vns_unique_en[['id']], how='left', indicator=True)  
vns_unique_en_release_matched = merged_vns[merged_vns['_merge'] == 'both'].drop('_merge', axis=1)  

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1)

ax[0].scatter(vns_unique_en_release_matched['release_date'], vns_unique_en_release_matched['c_average'], marker='x', alpha=.2, color='blue')
ax[0].set_title('Release Date vs Avg Score EN')
ax[0].set_xlabel('Release Date')
ax[0].set_ylabel('Average Score')

ax[1].scatter(vns_unique_en_release_matched['release_date'], vns_unique_en_release_matched['c_votecount'], marker='x', alpha=.2, color='blue')
ax[1].set_title('Release Date vs Popularity (Votecount) EN')
ax[1].set_xlabel('Release Date')
ax[1].set_ylabel('Popularity')

fig.set_figwidth(8)
fig.set_figheight(12)

The graph again does not show any strong correlation between release date and average score for the English releases, similar to the Japanese releases. The fact that newer games are more popular, however, has not changed. This suggests that many users tend to prefer more modern games that may have the edge in art, music, game engine performance, and quality of life features than their older counterparts.

Takeaways

The goal of our study was to explore some of the factors behind various visual novels' success, and to identify any key properties of a visual novel that might signify a successful western release. To that end, we have taken data from VNDB and analyzed properties of various visual novels such as its length, popularity (votecount), average vote score, and release date. And from our analysis, we have identified a few trends that might suggest a visual novel performs well in the West. Namely, longer visual novels tend to have generally higher scores while also having similar levels of popularity to shorter visual novels, suggesting that users enjoy longer games more when compared to shorter games. There also seems to be a bias towards newer visual novels in both Japanese-only and games that are available in English, suggesting that many users prefer more modern releases. However, it is also important to take a step back and examine the state of the community and market in different lenses as well. Specifically, I'd like to mention availability and convenience.

So what do availability and convenience really mean in the context of the visual novel market? Similar to other games, visual novels are released for different devices and storefronts, such as PC, console, and the Nintendo Switch as the main devices and stores such as Steam. The availability of a game on these various devices and stores greatly impact whether a user is willing to pay for and play a release. Notably Steam accounts for a major part in an official release's revenue - to the point where having a game get rejected from Steam is an enormous blow to its success. People value the convenience of having all of their favorite games available in one place greatly.

In the case of fan-translations, where a steam release is not available in the first place, this is less of a concern, as fan-translators are (usually) not translating out of desire for profit, but rather to share the experiences they have enjoyed with others. But as visual novels become increasingly popular in the west and official localizers are rapidly taking the place of fan-translations, the importance of availability and convenience is something that is to be ignored when considering the success of a western release.
